    <h1>Carbon Dioxide</h1>
    <p>Increased levels of carbon dioxide (CO2) in the Earth's atmosphere can have a range of environmental impacts. Some of the most significant impacts of increased CO2 levels include:
      Global warming: CO2 is a greenhouse gas, which means that it absorbs and traps heat in the Earth's atmosphere. As CO2 levels increase, more heat is trapped, leading to a rise in global temperatures. This can lead to a range of impacts, including more frequent heatwaves, droughts, and extreme weather events.
      Acidification of the oceans: CO2 dissolved in seawater can form carbonic acid, which can make the oceans more acidic. This can have serious impacts on marine life, particularly shellfish and coral reefs.
      Changes in ecosystems: As global temperatures rise, many species will be forced to adapt to new conditions or migrate to new areas. This can lead to changes in the balance of ecosystems and the loss of biodiversity.
      Impact on agriculture: Changes in temperature and precipitation patterns can affect crop yields and the distribution of pests and diseases. This can have serious consequences for food security.
      It's important to note that the magnitude and specific impacts of increased CO2 levels will vary depending on the region and the local environment.</p>
